	   <a name=101800545899794></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101800545899794><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101800545899794>RE: Stat discussion</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101800545899794#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=35651><span id=Guru>Keyeluke</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>670 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Apr 5th 6:17 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>OK Guys...&nbsp;&nbsp;Umojamon, the Prima Guide is loaded with mistakes, inaccuracies, errors, falsehoods, wishful thinking, etc.  If you have other, RELIABLE sources, please identify them.  Here is what has been quoted by Verant, tested by end-gamers, re-tested by others who used to think that stats were meaningful, etc:<br><br>Strength:  Increase your MAXIMUM damage.  It does not affect your modal damage, which is twice the weapons's damage modifier plus bonus if any.  Your modal damage is the damage you do most often - plot a histogram and you'll see a big spike at this number.  Str doesn't affect min damage either.  Testers indicate that a large shammy buff (50-100 Str) will increase your damage output maybe 2-3%.  Worth getting the Shammy buff?  Yes.  Worth getting enough Str gear to see that difference at the expense of HP/AC?  No.  Just because you see the occasional giant hit with a big strength buff doesn't mean that you're getting that hit all that often.<br><br>Str adds to your Attack score.  Attack is a combination of ability to hit and damage output.  Str only adds to the damage component, and again only in that it ups your highest potential damage number.  Since damage done per hit is highly biased towards the modal, moving the high end of the curve out to the right has only a small effect on your total melee output.<br><br>The only way to really tell the effect of strength is to parse LONG fights against a single mob (don't kill it - mob ac/hp/etc vary from respawn to respawn).  I can't be bothered - it's been beaten to death at Monkly Business.<br><br>Stamina.  Adds Hit points.  Get it to 100 and you suffer no melee output reduction if your yellow bar runs out.  At level 60, monks get 4 hp per point of stamina.  Translate stamina into hp gained and you'll be fine.<br><br>Agility.  Adds armor class in a very non-linear way.  If you get below 75, you take a BIG AC hit.  Above 100 it yields diminishing returns.  It also affects the rate at which you TRAIN your defensive skills.  It does NOT help you block/dodge, etc. beyond what appears in the form of extra AC.  We would all like to think that it does, but it doesn't.  Is it worth getting AGI buffs?  Yes.  Is it worth sacrificing HP/AC for?  No.<br><br>Dexterity.  Helps you learn weapon skills faster.  Somewhat improves the rate at which your weapons proc.  Same as before - don't chase the stat at the expense of HP/AC.  It does NOT affect your 'to hit' rate.  What DOES affect your 'to hit' rate are pure attack buffs.  Grim Aura, the epic effect, Boon of Garou (yes it adds attack in addition to dex) and others add pure, non-strength based attack.  They are highly desirable buffs.<br><br>Int/Wis - the higher of the two will help you with skillups on tradeskills (tho not on success rate from what I hear).  I keep Int gear in the bank specifically for my tradeskill work.<br><br>Cha - gets you better buy/sell prices at the vendor.  I keep a couple pieces in the bank - gets my Cha to 114 for selling.<br><br>Comments for Sloree:  For the melee stats, see above.  These are not my opinions, these are points of information that have been verified by the monk community.<br><br>An additional note on hit points, tanking, and damage dealing.  Monks through their early 50s often make better tanks than warriors.  After that, our lack of a taunt skill works against us.  Monks are invariably PULLERS.  As a puller, you want every last hit point you can get your hands on.  That 'one more hit' argument simply doesn't play.  I have close to 600 hp added from my gear, and I want more.  It doesn't come all in big chunks - I get it 35 here, 30 there, 25 there, etc. I cannot tell you the number of times I have feigned out with fewer than 50 HP.  My personal record is something like 13 I believe.  That's out of over 3000 buffed HP.  AC and HP are your friends when pulling - AC for the melee and HP for the casters.<br><br>Bottom line - combat stats are beneficial, but nowhere near as beneficial as HP/AC.  I translate Stamina into HP when I make gear comparisons, and use the other stats only as tie breakers.<br><br>Remember also that AC and HP do the same thing - they let you take more hits before dying.  AC reduces the average damage you take per hit, HP lets you take more hits.  They serve the same role, so they can be equated.  Most monks use a formula ranging from 10 HP = 1 AC down to 5 HP = 1 AC.  I use 8 HP = 1 AC for equipment comparison.<br><br>In fact, since I'm level 58 and close to the 4 HP = 1 Sta point, I use this formula:<br><br>8 HP = 1 AC = 2 Sta = 6 Agi<br><br>If there is Dex, that's a bonus.  I don't look for Str at all - if there's a shammy around, my Str ends up over 200 anyway.<br><br>Ketlo, destroy those serpentine bracers.  They are evil.  They lead monks down false paths.  If you're human, get two Symbols of Loyalty to Vox.  Best bang for the buck.<br><br>In general, at lower levels you should try to get straight HP adding equipment.  Silvery Mask adds 25, Ulthork Collar adds 30, and both are dirt cheap.  Orc fangs add 15 each, are also dirt cheap, and are better for monks IMO than the more expensive cougar claws.  Jewelers can sell you black sapphire electrum earrings and 6/65 rings, though that's a bit more pricey.<br><br>Anyway, the point I'm making is that, while melee stats do offer benefits, the benefits don't come close to the benefits offered by straight HP and AC gear, and you should never sacrifice HP/AC to gain stats.  I didn't make this stuff up - I'm repeating what has been said over and over by the monks who have played this game to its highest levels, who have tested the effects of stats, and who have convinced me after I put 10 points into agility, 4 into sta, 3 into str and 3 into dex that I should have gone all Stamina.  Not that it will break me now, but if it's advice I can pass forward, then all the better.<br><br>I now refer you to www.monkly-business.com to see all these same points repeated ad nauseum.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke<br>Member of Tenacity - Druzzil Ro<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a></td></tr>
